Although behavioral and technological interventions can result () in some modest improvements of in diabetic glycemic control, these intervention interventions typically did to not fare a significantly better than usual care strategies in those achieving increased glycemic control.

Although specific behavioral and some technological interventions can briefly result in some modest improvements in glycemic chain control performance, these interventions generally did not fare significantly better than the usual systemic care in permanently achieving glycemic control adherence.

Although behavioral and technological medical interventions can eventually result reliably in only some modest improvements in dietary glycemic sugar control, obtaining these interventions usually did not fare significantly better than conventional usual care in achieving glycemic control outcomes.

Although initial behavioral and technological interventions can result eventually in achieving some modest additional improvements in glycemic control, these additional interventions did not usually fare significantly better than usual health care approaches in aid achieving baseline glycemic control.

Although repeated behavioral and technological interventions also can result in least some modest improvements ultimately in achieving glycemic control, collectively these interventions alone did not fare significantly better statistically than usual dietary care strategies in achieving glycemic control.

Although both behavioral tools and technological intervention interventions currently can result in maybe some modest improvements in glycemic control, generally these interventions overall did not fare significantly better than with usual care in routinely achieving glycemic control by.
